                    <head>
                        <title>Cloz Miscellany (Codex Clozianus / Glagolita Clozianus / Codice Glagolitico Cloziano)</title>
                        <origDate notBefore="0996" notAfter="1017">End of the 10th or beginning of the 11th c.</origDate>
                        <origPlace ref="https://www.geonames.org/735355/makedonia.html">Macedonia</origPlace>
                        <note type="summary">From the original homiliary survive two fragments: 12 leaves are kept in Trento, 2 - in Innsbruck.</note>                      
                    </head>                    
                    <msContents>                      
                        <note>Preserved are five homilies for Palm Sunday and for somme of the days of Holy Week: two of which are complete (one by John Chrysostom and one by Athanasius of Alexandria); from the other three there are only fragments (one by John Chrysostom, one by Epiphanius of Salamis and one that is usually attributed to Methodius). </note>
                        </msItem>
                    </msContents>                    
                    <history>
                        <provenance>The manuscript was the property of the Frankopan family of the island of Krk in Dalmatia. The codex was named after the Count Paris Cloz who owned it in the first half of the 19th century. He donated the 12 leaves to the City Museum in Trent. The two folios kept today in Innsbruck were owned by Baron Andreas Di Pauli and discovered by the Slovene philologist Franz Miklosich (d. 1891).</provenance>
                    </history>
