                                <supportDesc material="perg">
                                    <support>
                                        <p>The <material>parchment</material> is most probably
                                            goat, the hair follicles are well
                                            visible; the hair sides are 1r and 2v, consequently the
                                            flesh sides are 1v and 2r. There are stains, which result
                                            from the colour of the goat. The upper edge of the bifolio
                                            seems to be stretched more than the rest, which hints toward
                                            the fact that this is the softer area of the skin, i.e.
                                            close to the belly. As the bifolio measures about 40 cm
                                            width from right to left, the goat might have been of app. 1
                                            meter length as it might have been positioned like “A” (cf.
                                            sketch by Jiri Vnoucek where the page with the initial is on
                                            the left and the upper edge of the bifolio on the
                                            right).</p>
                                        <p>The big <index indexName="SKOS.RESTORATION"><term ana="http://gams.uni-graz.at/thesaurus/hole">hole</term></index> in the middle of the bifolio was there before
                                            writing started; this hints toward the fact that even second
                                            class parchment was good enough for the codex. This is also
                                            indicated by the size of the skin, which hints towards a
                                            grown animal; consequently, the parchment maker did not
                                            strive to produce best possible quality, but took a skin he
                                            could reach.</p>
                                    </support>
                                    <extent>
                                        <measure type="leavesCount" quantity="2" unit="folio">1
                                            bifolium</measure>
                                        <dimensions type="leaf_current" unit="mm">
                                            <height/>
                                            <width>400</width>
                                        </dimensions>
                                    </extent>
                                    <condition>
                                        <p>In the centre of the fold we find remnants of the binding
                                            technique: i. e. slits 10 mm, 25mm, 160mm, 235mm and 250mm
                                            from the upper edge. However, there are also round sewing
                                            holes: 7 mm and 40 mm both pricked from outside. There are
                                            countless other piercings. They correspond with each other
                                            on both semifolios and were pierced from outside through to
                                            the second semifolio. The third use, so to speak, comes from
                                            the fact that the bifolio was folded twice to result in a 4
                                            layer piece of somewhat more than 100 mm x 144mm, perhaps to
                                            stiffen something like a book cover?</p>
                                        <p>
                                            <list>
                                                <head>Deletions</head>
                                                <item>There is a <index indexName="SKOS.RESTORATION"><term ana="http://gams.uni-graz.at/thesaurus/penknife">scraping with a knife</term></index> on the second
                                                    line from the bottom on the 3rd page in the
                                                    centre.</item>
                                                <item>There are also <index indexName="SKOS.RESTORATION"><term ana="http://gams.uni-graz.at/thesaurus/deletions">erased letters</term></index> at the beginning of
                                                    the 6th line from the bottom on the very same
                                                    page.</item>
                                            </list>
                                        </p>
                                        <p>
                                            <list>
                                                <head>Damages</head>
                                                <item>The bifolio is <index indexName="SKOS.RESTORATION"><term ana="http://gams.uni-graz.at/thesaurus/gelatinization">gelatinized</term></index>.</item>
                                                <item>There are some <index indexName="SKOS.RESTORATION"><term ana="http://gams.uni-graz.at/thesaurus/tear">tears</term></index>.</item>
                                                <item>There are also several <index indexName="SKOS.RESTORATION"><term ana="http://gams.uni-graz.at/thesaurus/cut">cuts</term></index>, one of which is on
                                                    the <locus from="2r">second folio</locus> in the corner and astonishingly
                                                    does not appear in the same position on the other
                                                    half of the folio.</item>
                                                <item>Another <index indexName="SKOS.RESTORATION"><term ana="http://gams.uni-graz.at/thesaurus/cut">cut</term></index> is in the upper area, which clearly
                                                    appeared after the parchment had been made and not
                                                    before, otherwise it would appear as a hole now as a
                                                    result of the stretching procedure.</item>
                                                <item>There is a <index indexName="SKOS.RESTORATION"><term ana="http://gams.uni-graz.at/thesaurus/stains">black stain </term></index> along the fold, possibly
                                                    char coal? Strong cross wise folds.</item>
                                                <item>On the upper edge a strong <index indexName="SKOS.RESTORATION"><term ana="http://gams.uni-graz.at/thesaurus/fold">fold</term></index>, possibly from
                                                    secondary use in a book binding.</item>
                                                <item><index indexName="SKOS.RESTORATION"><term ana="http://gams.uni-graz.at/thesaurus/mechanical">Broken parchment</term></index> along the folds and
                                                    elsewhere.</item>
                                                <item>There are numerous <index indexName="SKOS.RESTORATION"><term ana="http://gams.uni-graz.at/thesaurus/mechanical">scratches</term></index></item>
                                            </list>
                                        </p>
                                    </condition>
                                </supportDesc>
                                <layoutDesc>
                                    <layout ruledLines="40"> There are 40 lines on each folio,
                                        <dimensions type="lineHeight" unit="mm">
                                            <height>5</height>
                                        </dimensions> mm wide from each other, made with medium sharp
                                        tools from “inside”, i.e. solely from the flesh side. The lower
                                        two lines exceed the marginal lines towards the outer edge in an
                                        irregular way. They are terminated by 2 vertical lines on each
                                        page, 135 mm from each other. Prickings on the outer margins
                                        correspond with the line position. Interestingly, there is a
                                        groove along the pierced holes for the lines. They might
                                        represent rulings prior to pricking. That the prickings are on a
                                        “curved” line might derive from the distortion the parchment
                                        underwent over time. </layout>
                                </layoutDesc>
                            </objectDesc>
